    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah i figured it was a null pointer. i've already added some basic null checks like you said, but the error is still popping up occasionally. it's weird because the logs show the coupon ID is actually hitting the service, so it's like the object exists for a second and then just vanishes or fails to load right at the moment we need it. it feels almost random. any idea why it would be intermittent like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Intermittent failures like this, especially when the ID is present, often point to a race condition or a transient issue with your data access layer. It's very common in high-traffic scenarios, like when a few customers are trying to apply discounts at the exact same time, which can cause a temporary bottleneck, like a slow database query or a locking issue. You might need to investigate how your `Coupon` object is being fetched—perhaps the repository call is timing out or another process is modifying the coupon record right as your service tries to read it. Consider implementing a retry mechanism around the coupon fetching logic, or perhaps checking database connection pooling settings.",
      "source": "target",
